# Mobile-First Responsive Design

- Build every UI change mobile-first. Start with small screens, then enhance for tablet and desktop with `min-width` breakpoints.
- Keep the phone layout as the priority. Core content and actions must stay clear, readable, and usable on narrow screens.
- Prefer fluid sizing with `%`, `rem`, `clamp()`, `minmax()`, flexible grid/flex layouts, and `max-width` over fixed pixel widths.
- Avoid layouts that depend on hover, large viewports, or precise mouse interaction. Touch interaction must work well by default.
- Keep tap targets large enough, preserve readable text sizes, and maintain comfortable spacing on mobile.
- When editing pages or components, check that the result still looks intentional on phone and desktop, not only technically responsive.

## Example

```css
/* Good: mobile base, desktop enhancement */
.cardGrid {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 1fr;
}

@media (min-width: 768px) {
  .cardGrid {
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, minmax(0, 1fr));
  }
}
```
